UNDIAGNOSED DISEASE, BOVINE - TURKEY: IMPORTED ANIMALS, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
***************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Sun 20 Feb 2011
Source: Hurriyet Daily News & Economic Review, Bloomberg report [edited]
<http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/n.php?n=turkey-bans-import-of-austrian-cattle-on-bluetongue-suspicion-2011-02-20>


Turkey bans import of Austrian cattle on bluetongue suspicion
-------------------------------------------------------------
Turkey introduced an import ban on Austrian cattle last week after
bluetongue [BT], a viral disease that infects cows and sheep, was
detected in a sample from a selection of [imported] Austrian cows.

A Turkish laboratory said at least one test on cows imported from
Austria was positive, according to a spokesman for Austria's Ministry
of Health, who declined to be identified in line with ministry
policy. Austria sent a delegation to Turkey last week to take
samples, all of which tested negative and a laboratory in the UK is
currently cross-checking the samples, he said.

The tests were carried out after 5 Austrian cows died in Turkey and
15 cows that were in calf suffered stillbirths, Austria's Profil
magazine reported today [20 Feb 2011] without saying where it
obtained the information.

Austria hasn't had a case of bluetongue since 2008 and has carried
out 132 000 tests since then, all of which were negative, the
spokesman said. Bluetongue causes mouth ulcers in animals and in some
cases turns their tongues blue and can be fatal. The illness is
transmitted by [midge] bites. It poses no danger to humans.

--
